  "text": "Another group [CITATION_1] ) used a label-free quantitative proteomic analysis to investigate the effect of ethanol on central nervous system development in fetal brains of prenatally alcohol-treated C57BL/6 mice. Moderate prenatal alcohol exposure results in brain defects at different stages of development, interferes with the growth of the central nervous system, and induces neurodegeneration through cellular apoptosis. Pregnant mice were exposed from the 7th to the 13th embryonic day with either a 25% ethanol derived calorie diet or pair-fed liquid diet.",
